<HR>
<P>
For each of the following problems you will solve:
<ol type=I>
    <li>Before you begin writing code, design an appropriate algorithm using
	the <i>top-down</i> method.
    <li>Your <b>name</b>, <b>course</b>, <b>section</b>, <b>date</b>, and
	<b>assignment number</b> will appear as <u>comments</u> at the top of
	your source code.
    <P>
    <li>The <b>purpose</b> of the program will also appear as <u>comments</u>
	at the top of your source code.
    <P>
    <li>Follow closely the coding style of the text.<br>
	<u>Indent subordinate statements</u> and include comments explaining
	what the different parts of your program do.
    <P>
    <li>Compile your code with <tt>g++  -Wall </tt> <i>filename</i><tt>.cpp -o</tt> <i>filename</i> (ensure that there are no compiler warnings or errors)
    <P>
    <li>Use <b>script</b> on <i>csci</i> to generate a file which contains
    the source code followed by a demonstration of the (possibly
    interactive) running of your program (on on at least three examples of
    good test data, using data other than those in the examples below).
    (for each program) You will print out and hand in these files.
    <P>
    <li>Also, print and turn in copies of your <b>stubs</b> and
    <a href="#driver"><b>test driver</b> program</a>s.
</ol>
<P>
Be neat.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL>
    <li>Write a program which makes change from a dollar using the
    <u><i>fewest</i></u> number of bills and coins.<br>
      The function will fulfill the following specifications:
    <ul>
	<li>The <u>input</u> function will prompt the user for a <u>charge</u>
	(&lt; $500.00) and a <u>payment</u> (&lt;= $500.00)
	such that the payment exceeds the charge.
	<li>The <u>calculation</u> function will return the number of
	<ul>
	    <li>Hundreds
	    <li>Twenties
	    <li>Tens
	    <li>Fives
	    <li>Ones
	    <li>Quarters
	    <li>Dimes
	    <li>Nickels
	    <li>Pennies
	</ul>
	<li>The <u>output</u> function will output the change, listing the
	quantity of each denomination on its own line. 
    </ul>
    <li>Write a function which returns the <b>wind chill index</b> using the
    following formula [valid for Celsius temperatures of &lt;=10 degrees]:<br>
    <center>
	<tt><b>W</b> = 13.12 + 0.6215 * <b>t</b>
	    - 11.37 * <b>v</b><sup>0.16</sup>
	    + 0.3965 * <b>t</b> * <b>v</b><sup>0.16</sup></tt>
      </center>
      <br>
      where the variables are defined as:
    <ul>
	<li><tt><b>W</b></tt> is the wind chill index, based on the
	    <u>Celsius</u> temperature scale,
	<li><tt><b>t</b></tt> is the air temperature in
	    <i>degrees Celsius</i> (°C), 
	<li><tt><b>v</b></tt> is the air wind speed in
	    <i>kilometers-per-hour</i> (km/h), 
    </ul>
      <br>
      The function will fulfill the following specifications:
    <ul>
	<li> The function will expect and return temperatures in
	    <i>Fahrenheit</i> units.
	<li> The function will expect wind speeds in
	    <i>miles-per-hour</i> units.
	<li> The function will call helper functions to perform the 
	    units conversions
	    <li> The header documentation for each file will include a
	    listing of its
	    <a href="http://www.cs.ucf.edu/~reinhard/classes/cop3503/notes01.pdf"> preconditions and postconditions</a>.
    </ul>
      <br>
      Use the following <i>software engineering</i> techniques when developing
      your program:
    <ol>
	<li> Use <b>stubs</b> (as in <i>lab 5</i>) to validate your
	    program's structure.
	    <br>[this provides the <i>top-down</i> structure]
	<li> For each function that is represented by a stub, write and
	use a small <a href="#driver"><b>test driver</b> program</a>
	to validate
	    that the new function you have written to replace the stub is
	    working correctly before you replace the stub with that new
	    function.
	    <br> [this builds the program, ensuring correctness, from the
	    <i>bottom-up</i>]
	    <li> You can use tables from the Web for reference values to
	    test your functions, e.g.
	    <ul>

		<li><a href="http://www.msc.ec.gc.ca/education/windchill/windchill_chart_e.cfm">(Celsius -- kph) Wind-chill chart</a>.
		<li><a href="http://www.nws.noaa.gov/om/windchill/windchillchart3.pdf">(Fahrenheit -- mph) Wind-chill chart</a>.
		<li><a href="http://www.onlineconversion.com">Online Conversion</a>.
		<li><a href="http://www.sciencemadesimple.com/conversions.html">Online Metric Conversions</a>.
	    </ul>
    </ol>
</OL>
<P>
<h4><a name="driver">Test Driver Programs</a></h4>
<b>Test Driver Program</b>s are special programs whose only purpose is to test
functions.  They are very small.  They perform the following three tasks:
<ol>
    <li>Input values to test the function
    <li>Call the function with those input values
    <li>Output values from the function
</ol>
Ensure that you check that the input tests the <u>range</u> of the
preconditions and corresponds correctly with the output.<p>

